==Chinese==

===Glyph origin===
{{Han etym}}
In {{w|oracle bone inscriptions}} {{Han compound|廌|心|t1=antelope|ls=ic}}. The component {{lang|zh|心}} signified goodness, blessings and auspiciousness. 

In {{w|bronze inscriptions}} {{lang|zh|心}} is often also written as {{lang|zh|文}}. During the Warring states period, the tail of {{zh-l|*廌}} corrupted into {{lang|zh|个}}, then further into {{lang|zh|夂}} during the Qin dynasty. Based on the overlap between the many ancient variants of the character {{zh-ref|Ji, Xusheng (2004)}} suggests that {{zh-l|*麕}}, {{zh-l|*廌}}, {{zh-l|*麐}}, {{zh-l|*鹿}}  all refer to kinds of deer – beautiful and therefore worth celebrating when obtained. He also concludes that there is enough evidence that {{lang|zh|慶}} and {{zh-l|*麐}} were once the same character. Since {{lang|zh|麐}} was the most precious among deer, its character was used to express celebration.

===Etymology 1===
{{zh-forms|s=庆|alt=𢙎,𢞢,𢝑}}

Uncertain. {{zh-ref|Schuessler (2007)}} sees possible cognacy to {{cog|bo|གཡང||happiness, blessing, prosperity}}, which {{zh-ref|Bodman (1980)}} relates instead to {{och-l|祥}}.

